@NCAA According to https://dsn.dk/retskrivning/retskrivningsregler/a7-1-6/a7-5 the use of ¬¥ is voluntary. I'll leave the translation as-is.

@kbh4: I'm fully aware of this fact that you refer to.
That its use is considered voluntary doesn't mean that accent char shouldn't be applied though.
Especially in mobile apps often used on smaller screens, the use of accent chars helps the user to more quickly absorb messages, which means that it should be used extensively in this environment -- not based on spelling rules, but simply to aid the user to a better overall experience when reading texts in general in this environment.
Secondly, there're already approved DA outputs in this project containing the accent chars, so, to the user, this fact unnecessarily breaks the homogeneity in the project's use of the written language in Danish.
In conclusion, my recommendation is to definitely use the accent char wherever possible. It aids the ordinary reader (i.e. readers/users without any special training in specific methods of reading and interpretation) in their effort to understand messages, on the conscious as well as on the unconscious level (where the accent char aids on the unconscious level).
Personally, I always use the accent char based on the above argumentations. After all, as translators, our primary objectives are to convey messages/meanings/info etc. as precise as possible and in the easiest comprehensible way possible.

In German there are always two ways to refer to other people. The personal form ("versuche es erneut"), which you use for friends and people you know well, and the less personal and more polite form "versuchen Sie es erneut". Some apps only use one form, some only the other one. Mixing looks strange. I try to make all translations here "neutral" and thus avoiding either form (neutral also mixes with both forms). When neutral is not possible or sounds strange, I use the more polite form (looks more like a professional business product if you do).

Hi CodingMarkus! You're right, referring should be common accross all translations. So far, we have a mix of both variants - I felt like more of the current translation were using the informal way and went with it in my translations. It seems to be quite common to use the informal way within apps. The neutral form would of course elegantly avoid the issue - allthough I find it a bit artificial. @kspearrin , which of the two (or three) options do you prefer?

@NCAA I don't agree - it's used to set how many numbers should, at the minimum, be in a generated password. Concatenated "minimumcifre" sounds as referring to the value of the numbers. A better translation is "mindste antal cifre", but that string is to long for the GUI.

@kbh4: That's your prerogative of course.
However, had the alternate suggestion read "Minimumsciffer", your sentiments would've been correct. The current suggestion merely indicates "Min. antal cifre" (plural).
Unfortunately, in AE "number" and "digit" are used intercahangeably, which means many developers use the first option rather than the latter one. In my opinion, the latter one is the correct one since a password isn't a number per se, but rather a (random) selection of digits. That these digits form a number, well that's pretty much beside the point in this context.
A definite hurdle for translators is too short localization strings. It appears that many project owners don't take into accont the need for more space when localizing to certain languages, and this inspite of the fact that the crowdin platform covers this aspect as well. The problem just seems to be widely ignored by project owners, which regrettably leads to their software containing than optimal localization results.
I assume this is a direct result of two factors, firstly, that it requires quite a piece of work to ensure the optimum localization results for all project languages and secondly, that crowdin doesn't just charge a fixed subscription fee, but charges according to a number of utilization parameters as well, which may very well pose an economic challenge for smaller projects (companies).

@olavinto
When you are on a login field on your mobile device and Bitwarden detects it, you get that little "Bitwarden - My vault" button on your keyboard's toolbar. Tapping it opens the app, after which you can either tap on a matching login detail it has detected OR search for other ones in your vault.
If you do the latter and then tap on any of those login details, you get a little popup menu asking "Haluatko t√§ytt√§√§ kohteen automaattisesti vai tarkastella sit√§?" (string 1732?), with the options "Automaattit√§ytt√∂", "Automaattit√§yt√§ ja tallenna" and "N√§yt√§" below it.
So clearly the text on the first button is not right and should be matching the second button.
Admittedly this is not a menu you will see very often, because any login details that have a matching domain or app name saved on them will just be automatically recognized by Bitwarden. And tapping on those will just autofill them directly.
But there are some apps where Bitwarden does not automatically know which login detail they belong to. The Steam app for example (at least previously) was one of these, and I had to manually find the app's package name and add it as a URI under the login detail. Before doing that, or on any other apps that Bitwarden cannot automatically match to something, you'll be seeing this menu when you have to manually search for the login detail you want to autofill.
On Crowdin's context field it says this a verb, and there's a 7 year old comment stating it is one too. But I get that if they are also using this string in other places as a noun, it will inevitably be wrong in one place or another so who cares. Probably best to have it be proper in the places where it's visible more often.

The plural noun do not change but there is a rule that says:
‚ô• after numbers greater than 19 must be added the preposition "de":
ONE------------------TWO-------------------OTHER
1 zi-----------------19 zile---------------20 de zile (1 milion de zile) 1 orƒÉ----------------2-19 ore--------------20 de ore (1000 de ore) 1 sƒÉptƒÉm√¢nƒÉ----------2-19 sƒÉptƒÉm√¢ni--------20 de sƒÉptƒÉm√¢ni 1 an-----------------2-19 ani--------------20 de ani (66 de ani) 1 dolar--------------2-19 dolari-----------20 de dolari 1 euro---------- 2-19 euro-------------20 de euro
‚ô• Also, the preposition "de" is used in front of a second noun accompanied (determined) by the numeral, when thousands, millions and billions are rendered in words, and not in numbers: 20 "de" billions of euros.
1 leu---------------2-19 lei---------------20 de mii de lei
Exceptions:
a) ‚ô•‚ô•After decimals numbers, abbreviations and symbols, preposition "de" is not used b) ‚ô•‚ô•If the noun is abbreviated ex.: "m" for "milion"
1,25 francs---------2,85 francs-----------20, 45 francs 1 $-----------------2-19 $----------------20 $, 35 $ etc. 1 zi----------------2-19 zile-------------1 m zile (for 1 milion de zile) 1 RON---------------2-19 RON--------------20 RON, 58 RON etc

trans-unit.note:
"we" shouldn't be used in any ordinary UI texts except to indicate the involvement of staff in a given context such as problem-solving, user support, etc. In this particular case, no Bitwarden staff member is going to push a switch, etc. to make this popup appear. Contrary to the use in hardcopy media, this pronoun can be considered as intrusive, violating the user's privacy, and borderline offensive in certain circumstances, contexts, and phrasings when used in ordinary software UI strings/texts. In addition, using "we", "our" or "us" in ordinary UI texts doesn't benefit or enlighten the user in any way, and since the conventions for copywriting hardcopy and software texts aren't identical (contrary to what some seem to believe and claim), there's no real reason or need to ever use "we", "our" or "us" in ordinary UI texts. When the topic is legal matters, software aimed at kids, special-purpose software, games, etc., then this 'limitation' doesn't apply, at least no in quite the same way.

trans-unit.note:
To Brazilian translators: I've been thinking about a proper translation for "login/log in/logging in/etc" terms and variants.
Of course, it will depend on the context to see what fits best in each case, but in overall terms, we should have an standard for this.
There are words in specific that can fit in these cases: 1. "Login" (no translation); 2. "Entrar" ("to enter", like "signing in"); 3. "Acessar" ("to access").
In some cases the word "Login" itself would refer to credentials, so we could use "credencial(is)" for such scenarios.
There are other variations, but I believe these ones are the most relevant.
Please consider talking about these possibilities, so we can provide a better localization for these terms.
In my own opinion, I believe "acessar" would fit best in most of cases.
I'll review the remaining strings related to these terms as soon as this gets settled.

I don't think "suojausavain" is the correct word to use for translating "passkey".
That's what the physical security devices like YubiKeys and Titan Security Keys are called. All the big companies like Google, Microsoft and Apple use that word for them.
Better words for "passkey" would be "avainkoodi", which is what Google calls them, or "todentamisavain", which is the word Microsoft, Apple and others use.

@olavinto My logic for technical terms like these would be to just go based on what people will find if they were to look them up.
If someone installs the app and doesn't know what a "suojausavain" is yet, they will Google it. All the top links they will see will be for support articles on these big companies' sites, talking about the physical security key devices.
Whereas searching for "todentamisavain" or "avainkoodi" will actually get you links to passkey-related pages.
So I'm not saying we must use one of these two words just because they did so, these are just what I could come up with quickly. I am sure there are other words being used by others too (AFAIK passkeys are still a relatively new thing for normal sites/platforms like Google, so I get it's inconsistent).
I simply believe using this one specific term "suojausavain" doesn't seem like a good idea, when it's already being popularly used as the word for the security keys.
And yeah I see these are from a year ago, so I have no idea how these words were being used back then, whether any of those support pages for the big companies even existed yet (in Finnish at least), etc.
Either way, I got bored and re-did all the strings that had this word in them. I kept everything else the same as what had already been approved. Did them all twice, with both of the two alternative words I mentioned above. Maybe it saves you time if you decide to go with one of these instead. If not, not a big deal, lol.

@olavinto (& @dwbit): Thx.
Very commendable that you take the time to investigate such aspects, however, not all may have time to do that or are not, for whatever reason, inclined to do so, which is why such info should preferably be included in the CONTEXT section. The risk of omitting such info may be erroneous translations, i.e., based on guesswork ‚Äî I've seen many examples of this in various projects over the years.
It's far from all source texts that require context info, only the ones that may be ambiguous (like this source text), contain (certain) technical aspects/references, or are not otherwise straightforward in terms of meaning if one is but a layman.
Ideally, a translator shouldn't need to leave this platform (to look up external-based references, etc.) in order to perform localization tasks on crowdin.

@olavinto: Not a big surprise to hear about the calamities of messaging system. Bitwarden isn't alone in deciding not to rely on it, many other projects have had to make the same decision because they simply couldn't trust things like notifications to reach the right recipients in due time, just to mention one drawback of the system. Quite peculiar that crowdin haven't fixed this yet, as this issue has existed all the way back from when crowdin was initially launched to the broad public.
There is one other problem with this system, though, which is the misuse of it (massive spamming), at least as far as I've been told. According to a PM of one of the projects I contribute to, they typically received close to a thousand spam messages on a daily basis, which was why they had stopped using (and monitoring) the messaging system altogether. The only way to contact them directly is through email.

trans-unit.note:
We should be able to inflect the variable's strings to construct this sentence fluently. Now we are force to twist it into something wierd due to being forced to consider the uninflected base forms. Master password works here because we can freely use any form for it.
For an example: "PIN" would have to be PIN-koodilla which means exactly "with PIN code". Here [PIN-koodi] is the base form but in this case it needs [lla] ending. "Biometrics" would become "Biometrialla" (= "with biometrics"), and [Biometria][lla]. Same with "master password" which becomes [p√§√§salasana][lla].
Now, using a variable here is fine BUT only if the variable's strings are not used in other contexts that require forms other than this does. So basically this string should have its own strings OR there should simply be three (or however many are required) different variations of this whole sentence.
Since this is the Bitwarden mobile project, "app(s)" should generally be used rather than "application(s)".
